roduce ways to help everyone be able to communicate in an inclusive way. You can explore warm up games, <a href=\"http:\/\/dramaresource.com\/image-theatre\/\">still image theatre<\/a> and use of narrator \/ joker to bring everyone into the story.<\/p>\n<p>For us at EdLab, one particular area of interest is the effect of Digital Technology and new laws on our lives. Should we be able to communicate privately with each other digitally? What is the effect of bulk monitoring of all our communications? Where is the right trade off between safety from domestic attacks and the right to privacy? \u00a0<strong><br \/>\n<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>You can explore any issue that you think brings together the personal and political and is of interest to your target audience.<\/p>\n<p><!--more--><\/p>\n<p><strong>More information<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>This work builds on the foundations of <a href=\"https:\/\/scholar.google.co.uk\/scholar?hl=en&amp;q=augusto+boal\">Augusto Boal <\/a>whose work on Forum Theatre techniques were originally put to use in radical political settings of South America. <a href=\"http:\/\/www.bbc.co.uk\/education\/guides\/zxpc2hv\/revision\/8\">This summary of key moments work <\/a>also has a video clip from Cardboard Citizens outlining how they may be used.<\/p>\n<p>To get involved in this project, or to work on a challenge which supports the development of this project, contact m.chesterman@mmu.ac.uk or edlab@mmu.ac.uk<\/p>\n<p>Key Partner: This project is aimed at local schools or youth groups<\/p>\n<p>Key Words: Civic issues, digital issues, drama, forum theatre, games, spark the change<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>We often explore many of the issues that face us today through research and spoken debate. In a school setting this may involve presentations from teachers, supplementary reading, questions and a short discussion. Drama games and techniques offer radically different ways to explore contemporary political and personal aspects 